Sequence.name: NAESB.BaseCIM_CombinedVersion
Sequence.documentation: The combined version denotes the versions of the subpackages that have been combined into the total CIM model. This is a convenience instead of having to look at each subpackage.

DateTime.name: date
DateTime.documentation: Form is YYYY-MM-DD for example for January 5, 2009 it is 2009-01-05.

String.name: version
String.documentation: Form is IEC61970CIMXXvYY_IEC61968CIMXXvYY_combined where XX is the major CIM package version and the YY is the minor version, and different packages could have different major and minor versions. For example IEC61970CIM13v18_IEC61968CIM10v16_combined. Additional packages might be added in the future.

Sequence.name: NAESB.CustomerAgreement
Sequence.documentation: Agreement between the customer and the ServiceSupplier to pay for service at a specific service location. It provides for the recording of certain billing information about the type of service provided at the service location and is used during charge creation to determine the type of service.

String.name: name
String.documentation: The name is any free human readable and possibly non unique text naming the object.

Sequence.name: Customer

Array.name: CustomerAuthorisations

Array.name: ServiceDeliveryPoints

Sequence.name: NAESB.CustomerAuthorisation
Sequence.documentation: Holds an authorization for access to specific user-private data granted to a third party service provider.

String.name: authorizationServer
String.documentation: Contains the URI link to the authorization endpoint associated with this authorization.

Sequence.name: authorizedPeriod
Sequence.documentation: Restricts access to requests or subscriptions within this date time interval.

String.name: name
String.documentation: The name is any free human readable and possibly non unique text naming the object.

Sequence.name: validityInterval
Sequence.documentation: Date and time interval this agreement is valid (from going into effect to termination).

String.name: accessToken

Sequence.name: publishedPeriod

String.name: resource

Array.name: CustomerAgreements

Sequence.name: NAESB.ElectricPowerQualitySummary
Sequence.documentation: A summary of power quality events. This information represents a summary of power quality information typically required by energy management systems. It is not intended to satisfy the detailed requirements of power quality monitoring. All values are as defined by measurementProtocol during the period. The standards typically also give ranges of allowed values. See referenced standards for definition, measurement protocol and period.

Real.name: flickerPlt
Real.documentation: A measurement of long term Rapid Voltage Change

Real.name: flickerPst
Real.documentation: flickerPst is a value measured over 10 minutes that characterizes the likelihood that the voltage fluctuations would result in perceptible light flicker. A value of 1.0 is designed to represent the level that 50% of people would perceive flicker in a 60 watt incandescent bulb.

Real.name: harmonicVoltage
Real.documentation: A measurement of the Harmonic Voltage during the period. For DC, distortion is with respect to a signal of zero Hz.

Integer.name: longInterruptions
Integer.documentation: A count of Long Interruption events (as defined by measurementProtocol) during the summary interval period.

Real.name: mainsVoltage
Real.documentation: A measurement of the Mains [Signaling] Voltage during the summary interval period.

String.name: measurementProtocol
String.documentation: A reference to the source used as the measurement protocol definition. e.g., "IEEE1519-2009", "EN50160"

Real.name: powerFrequency
Real.documentation: A measurement of the power frequency during the summary interval period.

Integer.name: rapidVoltageChanges
Integer.documentation: A count of Rapid Voltage Change events during the summary interval period

Integer.name: shortInterruptions
Integer.documentation: A count of Short Interruption events during the summary interval period

Sequence.name: summaryInterval
Sequence.documentation: The relevant time reference for the ElectricPowerQualitySummary. This time interval may not be the same as any associated EMIntervalData time interval. For example, many of the statistics in the summary are running counts. The summaryInterval defines when the counts began.

Integer.name: supplyVoltageDips
Integer.documentation: A count of Supply Voltage Dip events during the summary interval period

Integer.name: supplyVoltageImbalance
Integer.documentation: A count of Supply Voltage Imbalance events during the summary interval period

Integer.name: supplyVoltageVariations
Integer.documentation: A count of Supply Voltage Variations during the summary interval period

Integer.name: tempOvervoltage
Integer.documentation: A count of Temporary Overvoltage events (as defined by measurementProtocol) during the summary interval period

Sequence.name: UsagePoint
Sequence.documentation: UsagePoint for this ElectricPowerQualitySummary.

Sequence.name: NAESB.EndDeviceAsset
Sequence.documentation: EndDeviceAsset that performs one or more end device functions. One type of EndDeviceAsset is a MeterAsset which can perform metering, load management, connect/disconnect, accounting functions, etc. Some EndDeviceAssets, such as ones monitoring and controlling air conditioner, refrigerator, pool pumps may be connected to a MeterAsset. All EndDeviceAssets may have communication capability defined by the associated ComFunction(s). An EndDeviceAsset may be owned by a consumer, an energy service provider, utility or otherwise. There may be a related end device function that identifies a sensor or control point within a metering application or communications systems (e.g., water, gas, electricity). Some devices may use an optical port that conforms to the ANSI C12.18 standard for communications.

String.name: name
String.documentation: The name is any free human readable and possibly non unique text naming the object.

Sequence.name: UsagePoint
Sequence.documentation: Usage point to which this end device asset belongs.

Sequence.documentation: Type of this name.

Sequence.name: NAESB.NameType
Sequence.documentation: Type of name. Possible values for attribute 'name' are implementation dependent but standard profiles may specify types. An enterprise may have multiple information technology systems each having its own local name for the same object, e.g., a planning system may have different names from an energy management system. An object may also have different names within the same system.

String.name: name

Array.name: Names

Sequence.documentation: Authority responsible for managing names of this type.

Sequence.name: NAESB.PositionPoint
Sequence.documentation: Set of spatial coordinates that determine a point, defined in coordinate system specified in 'Location.CoordinateSystem', or "WGS 84" if not specified otherwise. Use a single position point instance to describe a point-oriented location. Use a sequence of position points to describe a line-oriented object (physical location of non-point oriented objects like cables or lines), or area of an object (like a substation or a geographical zone - in this case, have first and last position point with the same values).

String.name: xPosition
String.documentation: X axis position.

String.name: yPosition
String.documentation: Y axis position.

String.name: zPosition
String.documentation: (if applicable) Z axis position.

Sequence.name: UsagePoint
Sequence.documentation: UsagePoint at thie PositionPoint (location).

Sequence.name: NAESB.Reading
Sequence.documentation: Specific value measured by a meter or other asset. Each Reading is associated with a specific ReadingType.

DateTime.name: timeStamp
DateTime.documentation: The time when the value was last updated

Array.name: MeterReadings
Array.documentation: All meter readings (sets of values) containing this reading value.

Array.name: ReadingQualities
Array.documentation: Used only if quality of this reading value is different than 'Good'.

Sequence.name: ReadingType
Sequence.documentation: Type information for this reading value.

Sequence.name: NAESB.ReadingQuality
Sequence.documentation: Quality of a specific reading value or interval reading value. Note that more than one quality may be applicable to a given reading. Typically not used unless problems or unusual conditions occur (i.e., quality for each reading is assumed to be 'good' unless stated otherwise in associated reading quality).

Enumerated.name: quality
Enumerated.documentation: Quality, to be specified if different than ReadingType.defaultQuality.

Sequence.name: IntervalReading
Sequence.documentation: Interval reading value to which this quality applies.

Sequence.name: Reading
Sequence.documentation: Reading value to which this quality applies.

Sequence.name: NAESB.ReadingType
Sequence.documentation: Detailed description for a type of a reading value. Values in attributes allow for the description of metadata about a measurement or measurements.

Enumerated.name: accumulation
Enumerated.documentation: Accumulation behavior of a reading over time, usually 'measuringPeriod', to be used with individual endpoints (as opposed to 'macroPeriod' and 'aggregate' that are used to describe aggregations of data from individual endpoints).

Enumerated.name: aggregate
Enumerated.documentation: Salient attribute of the reading data aggregated from individual endpoints. This is mainly used to define a mathematical operation carried out over 'macroPeriod', but may also be used to describe an attribute of the data when the 'macroPeriod' is not defined.

Sequence.name: argument
Sequence.documentation: Argument used to introduce numbers into the unit of measure description where they are needed (e.g., 4 where the measure needs an argument such as CEMI(n=4)). Most arguments used in practice however will be integers (i.e., 'denominator'=1). Value 0 in 'numerator' and 'denominator' means not applicable.

Enumerated.name: commodity
Enumerated.documentation: Commodity being measured.

Integer.name: consumptionTier
Integer.documentation: In case of common flat-rate pricing for power, in which all purchases are at a given rate, 'consumptionTier'=0. Otherwise, the value indicates the consumption tier, which can be used in conjunction with time of use or critical peak period pricing. Consumption tier pricing refers to the method of billing in which a certain "block" of energy is purchased/sold at one price, after which the next block of energy is purchased at another price, and so on, all throughout a defined period. At the start of the defined period, consumption is initially zero, and any usage is measured against the first consumption tier ('consumptionTier'=1). If this block of energy is consumed before the end of the period, energy consumption moves to be reconed against the second consumption tier ('consumptionTier'=2), and so on. At the end of the defined period, the consumption accumulator is reset, and usage within the 'consumptionTier'=1 restarts.

Integer.name: cpp
Integer.documentation: Critical peak period bucket the reading value is attributed to. Value 0 means not applicable. Even though critical peak period is usually considered a specialized form of time of use, this attribute is defined explicitly for flexibility.

Enumerated.name: currency
Enumerated.documentation: Metering-specific currency.

Enumerated.name: defaultQuality
Enumerated.documentation: The default quality of readings. It may be overridden for specific measurements in Reading or IntervalReading classes.

Enumerated.name: flowDirection
Enumerated.documentation: Flow direction for a reading where the direction of flow of the commodity is important (for electricity measurements this includes current, energy, power, and demand).

Sequence.name: interharmonic
Sequence.documentation: Indication of a "harmonic" or "interharmonic" basis for the measurement. Value 0 in 'numerator' and 'denominator' means not applicable.

String.name: intervalLength
String.documentation: (if incremental reading value) Length of increment interval.

Enumerated.name: macroPeriod
Enumerated.documentation: Time period of interest that reflects how the reading is viewed or captured over a long period of time.

Enumerated.name: measurementKind
Enumerated.documentation: Identifies "what" is being measured, as refinement of 'commodity'. When combined with 'unit', it provides detail to the unit of measure. For example, 'energy' with a unit of measure of 'kWh' indicates to the user that active energy is being measured, while with 'kVAh' or 'kVArh', it indicates apparent energy and reactive energy, respectively. 'power' can be combined in a similar way with various power units of measure: Distortion power ('distortionVoltAmperes') with 'kVA' is different from 'power' with 'kVA'.

Enumerated.name: measuringPeriod
Enumerated.documentation: Time attribute inherent or fundamental to the reading value (as opposed to 'macroPeriod' that supplies an "adjective" to describe aspects of a time period with regard to the measurement). It refers to the way the value was originally measured and not to the frequency at which it is reported or presented. For example, an hourly interval of consumption data would have value 'hourly' as an attribute. However in the case of an hourly sampled voltage value, the meterReadings schema would carry the 'hourly' interval size information. It is common for meters to report demand in a form that is measured over the course of a portion of an hour, while enterprise applications however commonly assume the demand (in kW or kVAr) normalised to 1 hour. The sytem that receives readings directly from the meter therefore must perform this transformation before publishing readings for use by the other enterprise systems. The scalar used is chosen based on the block size (not any sub-interval size).

Enumerated.name: multiplier
Enumerated.documentation: Metering-specific multiplier.

Enumerated.name: phases
Enumerated.documentation: Meteric-specific phase code.

Integer.name: tou
Integer.documentation: Time of use bucket the reading value is attributed to. Value 0 means not applicable.

Enumerated.name: unit
Enumerated.documentation: Metering-specific unit.

Array.name: IntervalBlocks
Array.documentation: All blocks containing interval reading values with this type information.

Array.name: MeterReadings
Array.documentation: MeterReadings with this ReadingType.

Array.name: Readings
Array.documentation: All reading values with this type information.

Sequence.name: ServiceSupplier
Sequence.documentation: ServiceSupplier able to use ReadingType.

Sequence.name: NAESB.ServiceCategory
Sequence.documentation: Category of service provided to the customer.

Enumerated.name: kind

Array.name: UsagePoint
Array.documentation: All service delivery points that deliver this category of service.

Sequence.name: NAESB.ServiceDeliveryPoint
Sequence.documentation: Logical point on the network where the ownership of the service changes hands. It is one of potentially many service points within a service location, delivering service in accordance with a customer agreement. Used at the place where a meter may be installed.

String.name: name
String.documentation: The name is any free human readable and possibly non unique text naming the object.

Sequence.name: CustomerAgreement
Sequence.documentation: Customer agreement regulating this service delivery point.

Sequence.name: TariffProfile
Sequence.documentation: TariffProfile governing this ServiceDeliveryPoint.

Array.name: UsagePoints
Array.documentation: UsagePoints at this ServiceDeliveryPoint

Sequence.name: NAESB.ServiceSupplier
Sequence.documentation: Organization that provides services to customers.

Enumerated.name: kind
Enumerated.documentation: Kind of supplier.

String.name: name
String.documentation: The name is any free human readable and possibly non unique text naming the object.

Array.name: Customers
Array.documentation: Customers supported by a ServiceSupplier.

Array.name: EnergyUsageInformation
Array.documentation: Collection of EnergyUsageInformation supported by this ServiceSupplier.

Array.name: ReadingTypes
Array.documentation: ReadingTypes supported by ServiceSupplier.

Sequence.name: NAESB.SummaryMeasurement
Sequence.documentation: An aggregated summary measurement reading.

Enumerated.name: powerOfTenMultiplier
Enumerated.documentation: The multiplier part of the unit of measure, e.g., "kilo" (k)

String.name: readingTypeRef
String.documentation: Reference to a full ReadingType that describes the measurement. Note only one of readingTypeRef or unit + powerofTenMultiplier are used in any single instance of SummaryMeasurement.

DateTime.name: timeStamp
DateTime.documentation: The date and time (if needed) of the summary measurement.

Enumerated.name: unit
Enumerated.documentation: The units of the reading, e.g., "Wh".

Real.name: value
Real.documentation: The value of the summary measurement.

Sequence.name: NAESB.TariffProfile
Sequence.documentation: A schedule of charges; structure associated with Tariff that allows the definition of complex tariff structures such as step and time of use.

String.name: name
String.documentation: The name is any free human readable and possibly non unique text naming the object.

Array.name: ServiceDeliveryPoints
Array.documentation: ServiceDeliveryPoints governed by a TariffProfile.

Sequence.name: NAESB.UsagePoint
Sequence.documentation: Logical point on a network at which consumption or production is either physically measured (e.g., metered) or estimated (e.g., unmetered street lights).

String.name: description
String.documentation: A human readable description of the object.

Boolean.name: isVirtual
Boolean.documentation: Is used to indicate that the UsagePoint is virtual (that is, not a real physical measurement). This may be the result of a computation or estimation.

String.name: name
String.documentation: The name is any free human readable and possibly non unique text naming the object.

Sequence.name: roleFlags
Sequence.documentation: The set of roles pertinent to this UsagePoint

Integer.name: status
Integer.documentation: Status of this UsagePoint: 0 - Off 1 - On

Sequence.name: Customer
Sequence.documentation: Customer associated with this UsagePoint

Array.name: ElectricPowerQualitySummaries
Array.documentation: ElectricPowerQualitySummaries at this UsagePoint.

Array.name: EndDeviceAssets
Array.documentation: All end device assets at this usage point.

Array.name: EnergyUsageInformation
Array.documentation: EnergyUsageInformation collection that this UsagePoint is part of.

Array.name: MeterReadings
Array.documentation: MeterReadings available at this UsagePoint.

Link.name: PositionPoint
Link.documentation: PositionPoint describing location of this UsagePoint.

Sequence.name: ServiceCategory
Sequence.documentation: Service category delivered by this service delivery point.

Array.name: ServiceDeliveryPoints
Array.documentation: ServiceDeliveryPoints associated with this UsagePoint.

Array.name: UsageSummaries
Array.documentation: UsageSummaries at this UsagePoint.

Sequence.name: NAESB.UsageSummary
Sequence.documentation: Summary of usage for a billing period. Note: This model was extended using the work of OpenADE 2015 for ESPI. These extensions are proposed for the next revision of the NAESB standard REQ.21. Also extended are SummaryMeasurement and LineDetail.

Sequence.name: billingPeriod
Sequence.documentation: The billing period to which the included measurements apply. May also be an off-bill arbitrary period.

Real.name: billLastPeriod
Real.documentation: The amount of the bill for the referenced billingPeriod in the currency attribute of this UsageSummary (e.g., 840 = USD, US dollar).

Real.name: billToDate
Real.documentation: If the summary contains data from a current period beyond the end of the referenced billingPeriod, the bill amount as of the date the summary is generated, in the currency attribute of this UsageSummary (e.g., 840 = USD, US dollar).

Enumerated.name: commodity
Enumerated.documentation: The commodity for this summary report.

Array.name: costAdditionalLastPeriod
Array.documentation: Additional charges from the for the referenced billingPeriod, in the currency attribute of this UsageSummary (e.g., 840 = USD, US dollar).

Array.name: costAdditionalLastPeriodDetail
Array.documentation: Additional charges from the for the referenced billingPeriod which in total add up to costAdditionalLastPeriod, in the currency attribute of this UsageSummary (e.g., 840 = USD, US dollar).

Enumerated.name: currency
Enumerated.documentation: The ISO 4217 code indicating the currency applicable to the bill amounts in the summary. See list at http://www.unece.org/cefact/recommendations/rec09/rec09_ecetrd203.pdf

Sequence.name: currentBillingPeriodOverallConsumption
Sequence.documentation: The total consumption for the billing period.

Sequence.name: currentDayLastYearNetConsumption
Sequence.documentation: The amount of energy consumed one year ago interpreted as same day of week same week of year (see ISO 8601).

Sequence.name: currentDayNetConsumption
Sequence.documentation: Net consumption for the current day (delivered - received).

Sequence.name: currentDayOverallConsumption
Sequence.documentation: Overall energy consumption for the current day.

Sequence.name: overallConsumptionLastPeriod
Sequence.documentation: The amount of energy consumed in for the referenced billingPeriod.

Sequence.name: peakDemand
Sequence.documentation: If the summary contains data from a current period beyond the end of the referenced billingPeriod, peak demand recorded for the current period.

Sequence.name: previousDayLastYearOverallConsumption
Sequence.documentation: If the summary contains data from a current period beyond the end of the referenced billingPeriod, the amount of energy consumed on the previous day one year ago interpreted as same day of week same week of year (see ISO 8601) based on the day of the statusTimestamp.

Sequence.name: previousDayNetConsumption
Sequence.documentation: If the summary contains data from a current period beyond the end of the referenced billingPeriod, net consumption for the previous day relative to the day of the statusTimestamp.

Sequence.name: previousDayOverallConsumption
Sequence.documentation: If the summary contains data from a current period beyond the end of the referenced billingPeriod, the total consumption for the previous day based on the day of the statusTimestamp.

Enumerated.name: qualityOfReading
Enumerated.documentation: Indication of the quality of the summary readings

Sequence.name: ratchetDemand
Sequence.documentation: If the summary contains data from a current period beyond the end of the referenced billingPeriod, the current ratchet demand value for the ratchet demand over the ratchetDemandPeriod.

Sequence.name: ratchetDemandPeriod
Sequence.documentation: The period over which the ratchet demand applies.

Sequence.name: UsagePoint
Sequence.documentation: UsagePoint for this UsageSummary.

Sequence.name: NAESB.RoleFlags
Sequence.documentation: Describes a set of specific communication or physical attributes that the associated UsagePoint has. The term RoleFlags in this specific case pertains to the application-specific nature of the UsagePoint. More than one of these flags can be true for any UsagePoint.

Boolean.name: isDC
Boolean.documentation: Is direct current (DC) rather than alternating current (AC)

Boolean.name: isMirror
Boolean.documentation: Represents a copy or mirror of an original UsagePoint

Boolean.name: isOneway
Boolean.documentation: Device is a one-way communications device that can only transmit its information and cannot receive.

Boolean.name: isPremiseAggregationPoint
Boolean.documentation: This UsagePoint aggregates the contributions of other UsagePoints in the premise

Boolean.name: isVirtual
Boolean.documentation: Is used to indicate that the UsagePoint is virtual (that is, not a real physical measurement). This may be the result of a computation or estimation. Note that isVirtual was added to IEC 61968-9 2nd ed model of a UsagePoint which occurred after its adoption by NAESB. It has since been added to Green Button and will be added to the next release of "NAESB Business Practices and Information Models to Support Priority Action Plan 10 - Standardized Energy Usage Information standards, Revision 1.1, 2012.

Sequence.name: NAESB.ReadingInterharmonic
Sequence.documentation: Interharmonics are represented as a rational number 'numerator' / 'denominator', and harmonics are represented using the same mechanism and identified by 'denominator'=1.

Integer.name: numerator
Integer.documentation: Interharmonic numerator. Value 0 means not applicable. Value 1 is used in combination with 'denominator'=2 to represent interharmonic 1/2, and with 'denominator'=1 it represents fundamental frequency. Finally, values greater than 1 indicate the harmonic of that order (e.g., 'numerator'=5 is the fifth harmonic).

Integer.name: denominator
Integer.documentation: Interharmonic denominator. Value 0 means not applicable. Value 2 is used in combination with 'numerator'=1 to represent interharmonic 1/2. Finally, value 1 indicates the harmonic of the order specified with 'numerator'.

Sequence.name: NAESB.RationalNumber
Sequence.documentation: Rational number = 'numerator' / 'denominator'.

Integer.name: denominator
Integer.documentation: Denominator. Value 1 indicates the number is a simple integer.

Enumerated.name: NAESB.FlowDirectionKind
Enumerated.documentation: This value identifies the direction of flow of what is being measured. Specific indications are supported, especially for electrical measurements that have complex values.

Unsigned.name: forward
Unsigned.documentation: "Delivered," or "Imported" as defined 61968-2. Forward Active Energy is a positive kWh value as one would naturally expect to find as energy is supplied by the utility and consumed at the service.

Enumerated.name: NAESB.MeasurementKind
Enumerated.documentation: Identifies "what" is being measured, as refinement of 'commodity'. When combined with 'unit', it provides detail to the unit of measure. For example, 'energy' with a unit of measure of 'kWh' indicates to the user that active energy is being measured, while with 'kVAh' or 'kVArh', it indicates apparent energy and reactive energy, respectively. 'power' can be combined in a similar way with various power units of measure: Distortion power ('distortionVoltAmperes') with 'kVA' is different from 'power' with 'kVA'.

Unsigned.name: ieee1366ASIDI
Unsigned.documentation: IEEE1366 Average System Interruption Duration Index (ASIDI)

Unsigned.name: ieee1366ASIFI
Unsigned.documentation: IEEE1366 Average System Interruption Frequency Index (ASIFI)

Unsigned.name: ieee1366CAIDI
Unsigned.documentation: IEEE1366 Customer Average Interruption Duration Index (CAIDI)

Unsigned.name: ieee1366CAIFI
Unsigned.documentation: IEEE1366 Customer Average Interruption Frequency Index (CAIFI)

Unsigned.name: ieee1366CEMSMIn
Unsigned.documentation: IEEE 1366 Customers Experiencing Multiple Sustained Interruption and Momentary Interruption Events (CEMSMIN)

Unsigned.name: ieee1366CTAIDI
Unsigned.documentation: IEEE 1366 Customers Experiencing Multiple Sustained Interruption and Momentary Interruption Events (CEMSMIN)

Unsigned.name: ieee1366MAIFI
Unsigned.documentation: IEEE 1366 Momentary Average Interruption Frequency Index (MAIFI)

Unsigned.name: ieee1366MAIFIe
Unsigned.documentation: IEEE 1366 Momentary Average Interruption Event Frequency Index (MAIFIE)

Unsigned.name: ieee1366SAIDI
Unsigned.documentation: IEEE 1366 System average interruption duration index (SAIDI)

Unsigned.name: ieee1366SAIFI
Unsigned.documentation: IEEE 1366 System average interruption frequency index (SAIFI)

Unsigned.name: frequencyExcursion
Unsigned.documentation: Frequency excursion. Usually expressed as a “count”.

Unsigned.name: demandReset
Unsigned.documentation: Demand resets. Usually expressed as a count as part of a billing cycle.

Unsigned.name: billLastPeriod
Unsigned.documentation: Customer’s bill for the previous billing period (Currency)

Unsigned.name: billToDate
Unsigned.documentation: Customer’s bill, as known thus far within the present billing period (Currency)

Unsigned.name: connectionFee
Unsigned.documentation: Monthly fee for connection to commodity.

Enumerated.name: NAESB.ServiceKind
Enumerated.documentation: Kind of service.

Enumerated.name: NAESB.SupplierKind
Enumerated.documentation: Kind of supplier.

Enumerated.name: NAESB.AccumulationKind
Enumerated.documentation: This attribute provides metadata about how the measurements described are made. These enumerated values refer to the common present and historic methods by which physical measurements are made in revenue-quality metering instruments and are based on that terminology.

Unsigned.name: none
Unsigned.documentation: Not Applicable, or implied by the unit of measure.

Unsigned.name: bulkQuantity
Unsigned.documentation: A value from a register which represents the bulk quantity of a commodity. This quantity is computed as the integral of the commodity usage rate. This value is typically used as the basis for the dial reading at the meter, and as a result, will roll over upon reaching a maximum dial value. Note 1: With the metering system, the roll-over behavior typically implies a roll-under behavior so that the value presented is always a positive value (e.g., unsigned integer or positive decimal.) However, when communicating data between enterprise applications a negative value might occur in a case such as net metering. Note 2: A BulkQuantity refers primarily to the dial reading and not the consumption over a specific period of time.

Unsigned.name: continuousCumulative
Unsigned.documentation: The sum of the previous billing period values and the present period value. Note: “ContinuousCumulative” is commonly used in conjunction with “demand.” The “ContinuousCumulative Demand” would be the cumulative sum of the previous billing period maximum demand values (as occurring with each demand reset) summed with the present period maximum demand value (which has yet to be reset.)

Unsigned.name: cumulative
Unsigned.documentation: The sum of the previous billing period values. Note: “Cumulative” is commonly used in conjunction with “demand.” Each demand reset causes the maximum demand value for the present billing period (since the last demand reset) to accumulate as an accumulative total of all maximum demands. So instead of “zeroing” the demand register, a demand reset has the affect of adding the present maximum demand to this accumulating total.

Unsigned.name: deltaData
Unsigned.documentation: The difference between the value at the end of the prescribed interval and the beginning of the interval. This is used for incremental interval data. Note: One common application would be for load profile data, another use might be to report the number of events within an interval (such as the number of equipment energizations within the specified period of time.)

Unsigned.name: indicating
Unsigned.documentation: As if a needle is swung out on the meter face to a value to indicate the current value. (Note: An “indicating” value is typically measured over hundreds of milliseconds or greater, or may imply a “pusher” mechanism to capture a value. Compare this to “instantaneous” which is measured over a shorter period of time.)

Unsigned.name: summation
Unsigned.documentation: A form of accumulation which is selective with respect to time. Note : “Summation” could be considered a specialization of “Bulk Quantity” according to the rules of inheritance where “Summation” selectively accumulates pulses over a timing pattern, and “BulkQuantity” accumulates pulses all of the time.

Unsigned.name: timeDelay
Unsigned.documentation: A form of computation which introduces a time delay characteristic to the data value

Unsigned.name: instantaneous
Unsigned.documentation: Typically measured over the fastest period of time allowed by the definition of the metric (usually milliseconds or tens of milliseconds.) (Note: “Instantaneous” was moved to attribute #3 in 61968-9Ed2 from attribute #1 in 61968-9Ed1.)

Unsigned.name: latchingQuantity
Unsigned.documentation: When this description is applied to a metered value, it implies that the value is a time-independent cumulative quantity much a BulkQuantity, except that it latches upon the maximum value upon reaching that value. Any additional accumulation (positive or negative) is discarded until a reset occurs. Note: A LatchingQuantity may also occur in the downward direction – upon reaching a minimum value. The terms “maximum” or “minimum” will usually be included as an attribute when this type of accumulation behaviour is present. When this description is applied to an encoded value (UOM= “Code”), it implies that the value has one or more bits which are latching. The condition that caused the bit to be set may have long since evaporated. In either case, the timestamp that accompanies the value may not coincide with the moment the value was initially set. In both cases a system will need to perform an operation to clear the latched value.

Unsigned.name: boundedQuantity
Unsigned.documentation: A time-independent cumulative quantity such as BulkQuantity or a LatchingQuantity, except that the accumulation stops at the maximum or minimum values. When the maximum is reached, any additional positive accumulation is discarded, but negative accumulation may be accepted (thus lowering the counter.) Likewise, when the negative bound is reached, any additional negative accumulation is discarded, but positive accumulation is accepted (thus increasing the counter.)

Enumerated.name: NAESB.CommodityKind
Enumerated.documentation: Identifies the commodity being measured.

Unsigned.name: electricity SecondaryMetered
Unsigned.documentation: All types of metered quantities. This type of reading comes from the meter and represents a “secondary” metered value.

Unsigned.name: electricity PrimaryMetere
Unsigned.documentation: It is possible for a meter to be outfitted with an external VT and/or CT. The meter might not be aware of these devices, and the display not compensate for their presence. Ultimately, when these scalars are applied, the value that represents the service value is called the “primary metered” value. The “index” in sub-category 3 mirrors those of sub-category 0.

Unsigned.name: communication
Unsigned.documentation: A measurement of the communication infrastructure itself.

Unsigned.name: insulativeGas
Unsigned.documentation: Insulative gas (SF6 is found separately below.)

Unsigned.name: steam
Unsigned.documentation: Water in steam form, usually used for heating.

Unsigned.name: heatingFluid
Unsigned.documentation: This fluid is likely in liquid form. It is not necessarily water or water based. The warm fluid returns cooler than when it was sent. The heat conveyed may be metered.

Unsigned.name: coolingFluid
Unsigned.documentation: The cool fluid returns warmer than when it was sent. The heat conveyed may be metered.

Unsigned.name: nonpotableWater
Unsigned.documentation: Reclaimed water – possibly used for irrigation but not sufficiently treated to be considered safe for drinking.

Unsigned.name: dissolvedCombustibleGas
Unsigned.documentation: Dissolved Combustible Gas (A combination of combustible gasses such as H2, CH4, C2H2, C2H4, C2H6, and/or CO in some mixture.)

Unsigned.name: pm10
Unsigned.documentation: Particulate matter whose maximum size is 10 µm.

Unsigned.name: pm25
Unsigned.documentation: Particulate matter whose maximum size is 2.5 µm.

Enumerated.name: NAESB.DataQualifierKind
Enumerated.documentation: This value qualifies the measurement as to what it represents -- for example a minimum or maximum value or a nominal or nameplate value.

Unsigned.name: high
Unsigned.documentation: Typically used to identify the high volume flow port of a compound water meter.

Unsigned.name: low
Unsigned.documentation: Typically used to identify the low volume flow port of a compound water meter.

Unsigned.name: excess
Unsigned.documentation: The value represents an amount over which a threshold was exceeded.

Unsigned.name: highThreshold
Unsigned.documentation: The value represents a programmed threshold.

Unsigned.name: lowThreshold
Unsigned.documentation: The value represents a programmed threshold.

Unsigned.name: nominal
Unsigned.documentation: The value represents nominal or nameplate values

Unsigned.name: normal
Unsigned.documentation: The value represents typical operating values

Enumerated.name: NAESB.MacroPeriodKind
Enumerated.documentation: Time period of interest that reflects how the reading is viewed or captured over a long period of time.

Unsigned.name: billingPeriod
Unsigned.documentation: Captured during the billing period starting at midnight of the first day of the billing period (as defined by the billing cycle day). If during the current billing period, it specifies a period from the start of the current billing period until "now".

Unsigned.name: daily
Unsigned.documentation: Daily Period starting at midnight. If for the current day, this specifies the time from midnight to "now".

Unsigned.name: monthly
Unsigned.documentation: Monthly period starting at midnight on the first day of the month. If within the current month, this specifies the period from the start of the month until "now."

Unsigned.name: seasonal
Unsigned.documentation: A season of time spanning multiple months. E.g., "Summer," "Spring," "Fall," and "Winter" based cycle. If within the current season, it specifies the period from the start of the current season until "now."

Unsigned.name: weekly
Unsigned.documentation: Weekly period starting at midnight on the first day of the week and ending the instant before midnight the last day of the week. If within the current week, it specifies the period from the start of the week until "now."

Unsigned.name: specifiedPeriod
Unsigned.documentation: The period defined by the start time and end time of the MeterReading.valuesInterval associated with the containing ReadingType.

Enumerated.name: NAESB.MeasuringPeriodKind
Enumerated.documentation: Time attribute inherent or fundamental to the reading value (as opposed to 'macroPeriod' that supplies an "adjective" to describe aspects of a time period with regard to the measurement). It refers to the way the value was originally measured and not to the frequency at which it is reported or presented. For example, an hourly interval of consumption data would have value 'hourly' as an attribute. However in the case of an hourly sampled voltage value, the meterReadings schema would carry the 'hourly' interval size information. It is common for meters to report demand in a form that is measured over the course of a portion of an hour, while enterprise applications however commonly assume the demand (in kW or kVAr) normalized to 1 hour. The system that receives readings directly from the meter therefore performs this transformation before publishing readings for use by the other enterprise systems. The scalar used is chosen based on the block size (not any sub-interval size).

Unsigned.name: present
Unsigned.documentation: Within the present period of time

Unsigned.name: previous
Unsigned.documentation: Shifted within the previous monthly cycle and data set

Enumerated.name: NAESB.PhaseCodeKind
Enumerated.documentation: Enumeration of phase identifiers. Allows designation of phases for both transmission and distribution equipment, circuits and loads. Residential and small commercial loads are often served from single-phase, or split-phase, secondary circuits. Phases 1 and 2 refer to hot wires that are 180 degrees out of phase, while N refers to the neutral wire. Through single-phase transformer connections, these secondary circuits may be served from one or two of the primary phases A, B, and C. For three-phase loads, use the A, B, C phase codes instead of s12N.

Unsigned.name: phaseCtoAv
Unsigned.documentation: Phase C current or voltage relative to Phase A voltage

Unsigned.name: phaseBtoAv
Unsigned.documentation: Phase B current or voltage relative to Phase A voltage

Unsigned.name: phaseAtoAv
Unsigned.documentation: Phase A current relative to Phase A voltage

Enumerated.name: NAESB.TimeAttributeKind
Enumerated.documentation: This value identifies the time period during which this measurement was performed. For example if averaged (see DataQualifierKind) what period is averaged. Other complex time periods for how a measurement is computed are identified.

Unsigned.name: specifiedInterval
Unsigned.documentation: The interval length is described in RationalNumber.numerator in seconds. Attribute RationalNumber.denominator should be ‘1’ for whole seconds.

Unsigned.name: specifiedFixedBlock
Unsigned.documentation: The fixed block duration is described in RationalNumber.numerator in seconds. RationalNumber.denominator should be ‘1’ for whole seconds.

Unsigned.name: specifiedRollingBlock
Unsigned.documentation: The rolling block size is described by RationalNumber.numerator in seconds, and the sub-interval size by RationalNumber.denominator in seconds.

Unsigned.name: present
Unsigned.documentation: Within the present period of time

Unsigned.name: previous
Unsigned.documentation: Shifted within the previous monthly cycle and data set
